etymologies: Middle English. From Anglo-Norman cliket, cleket, clequet, kliket and Middle French cliquet, clicquet leper's rattle, clap-dish, latch, bolt, clapper of a mill, chatter, nattering, (plural) a type of rattle or castanet, lid of a container from Old French cliketer

definitions: The latch of a door or gate.
A catch, holdfast, bolt, etc., that fastens something by falling or springing into position.

etymologies: late Middle English (in an earlier sense). Originally from clicket

definitions: To make, or cause something to make, a click or clicking sound; = "click".
